How are ratings calculated?
To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzes reviews to verify trustworthiness.

5.0 out of 5 stars 5900X w/ Gigabyte X570 Ultra Rev 1.0
Reviewed in the United States on November 22, 2020
Verified Purchase
So far compared to my 3900x this is definitely running much faster and allows me to run my memory at 3800/1900 FCLK. My 3900x silicone lottery was terrible and would not run anything higher then 3600/1800 FCLK.

Jason D.
VINE VOICE
5.0 out of 5 stars 4.7GHz @ 1.325v on air.........am I dreaming???
Reviewed in the United States on December 6, 2020
Verified Purchase
Yes, you read the headline correct. Someone wake me up because I can't believe I am seeing this. 4.7GHz on all 12 cores (24 threads) at only 1.325v on the core. I do have my load line calibration set to Extreme so under full 100% load with a synthetic stress test the core voltage increases to a max of 1.392v but still.......4.7GHz on all 12 cores air cooled!! I'm running a Gigabyte X570 AORUS Xtreme motherboard and a Noctua NH-D15 air cooler with IC Diamond thermal paste. I am hitting 85-86C max temp but that's only while running the stress test. Idle is still 38C and other than running a stress test it's cool as a cucumber. With better cooling I could get a LOT more out of it, I just know it. In regards to power draw, while running the stress test the cpu is pulling 214 watts and 142 amps. I can't believe I can run all of this on air. The highest I've been able to clock a cpu on air over the past decade is 4.5GHz and that was really pushing it to the limit and that was only with a 6 core Intel. This 5900X is 12 cores! All I can say is WOW, I am super impressed. This makes me want to go back to water cooling for sure, lol.

Cinebench R20 score fluctuates but the highest I have gotten is 9208. This score is purely dictated by temperature. The cooler rye cpu is the higher the score is, for the 5900X anyway.

Other components this cpu is being installed with are:
Gigabyte AORUS X570 Xtreme
32GB (8GB x 4) Corsair 3600Mhz CL14 memory
Samsung PCIe 4.0 980 Pro NVMe drive
MSI GeForce RTX Ventus 3X OC 3090
Corsair HX750i power supply
LG 3840x1600 160Hz ultrawide monitor

While playing Call of Duty Cold War with all the Ray Tracing and other eye candy maxed out Im seeing a max of 110-120fps. The 3090 is absolutely maxed out, Its even using all 24GBs of its vram and 14GBs of my system ram. This 5900X is just chugging along at about 50% utilization at a comfortable 64C. If this were the smaller 5600X it would be 100% maxed out so having the extra cores is definitely a huge benefit for gaming, not to mention the higher clock speed you get with the 5900X.

Whatever you have to do to get one of these I say DO IT!! This thing is a beast. Fyi, there are live streams on YouTube that notify you when these things are in stock. Its how I finally got my hands on this one. Check them out........youre welcome. :)

5.0 out of 5 stars Great CPU from AMD - lives up to the hype
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on February 22, 2021
Verified Purchase
I like many others was sceptical about AMD, after all they let us down with previous CPUs losing to Intel on gaming, multiple bios screw ups for their mobos, and screwed up multiple drivers for their GPUs (still doing that actually).

BUT, this CPU is a monster. Demolishing Intels 10900k flagship on single core & multi-core (in most benchmarks).
I couldn't ignore the combined data from benchmarks any longer (gaming + productivity), and real-world gaming performance benefits.
Its also no suprise that AMD were able to fit 12-16 cores on 7nm vs Intel who just scaled back to 8 cores and added another + to their 14nm. They're beyond a meme at this point, they're just a joke.

Pair this CPU with a new B550 motherboard (180-200 ish) which use the new fanless chipset design, and you've got yourself a bang up to date system that will last years. Gone are the days where you need to spend 400-500 on a board. I'd recommend the Asus TUF or Strix with built in wi-fi.

Perfect when paired with an Nvidia 3000 series card & a gsync monitor - because even given the performance benefit of an all AMD system (10% max), the RTX3080 is also a monster which is hard to ignore (especially with DLSS on).

+ Performance, top notch (2 best CPUs in 2021 will be 5900x & 5950x)
+ 5.5-5.7Ghz all core easy OC achievable out of the box (prepare your power supply)
+ Easy to install
= You'll get a lot of flak from idiots citing 2003 logic as to why AMD are crap
- Pain in the A trying to figure out if the mobo you want has the 5*** series bios pre-installed or not
- Very poor value for money

However, I would not encourage anybody to buy this above its RRP. Its not worth enabling scalpers. It will be back in stock at retail prices.
